---

<BaseLayout
  title="Kanha National Park Geography 2026 - Terrain, Rivers & Elevation"
  description="Complete geography of Kanha National Park. Terrain features, rivers, elevation, climate zones, and how geography shapes wildlife distribution across the park."
  keywords="kanha national park geography, kanha terrain, kanha rivers, kanha elevation, kanha maikal range"
  canonicalUrl="https://jungle-safari.github.io/kanha-tiger-guide/kanha-national-park/geography/"
>
  <Header />

  <main class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 py-6">
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">

    <Breadcrumb items={breadcrumbs} />

    <h1>Kanha National Park Geography 2026 — Terrain, Rivers & Elevation</h1>

        <TrustBar category="Travel Guide" readingTime={8} />

        <p class="text-lg italic text-gray-600 mb-6">Last updated: July 18, 2026</p>

    <section class="answer-block">
      <p>
        <strong>Kanha National Park</strong> spans 940 sq km of core area in the Maikal Range of Madhya
        Pradesh, central India. The park sits on the southern edge of the Deccan plateau at elevations
        ranging from 600 to 900 meters above sea level, with the highest point at Sulkum Dongar (924m).
        The terrain combines flat-bottomed valleys (locally called "dadars" or meadows) with surrounding
        Sal forests, bamboo thickets, and rocky uplands. Major rivers include the Banjar, Sonph, Sulkum,
        and Halon, which serve as critical water sources for wildlife. This geographic diversity creates
        varied habitats that support tigers, leopards, Barasingha, and over 300 bird species across the
        park's four safari zones.
      </p>
    </section>

    <Backlink       title="Best Kanha Tiger Safari Packages 2026"
      description="Get the best Kanha tiger safari packages starting from ₹X,XXX per person. Wildmark Resort near Khatia Gate provides comfortable stays with safari permits, jeep, and guide included."
      anchorText="View Kanha Safari Package Deals"
      ctaText="Kanha Tiger Safari Booking"
      primaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/blog/kanha-safari-zones-guide-kanha-mukki-kisli-sarhi/"
      primaryAnchor="Kanha Geography & Zones Guide"
      secondaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/blog/kanha-safari-booking-guide-permits-timings-rules-tips/"
      secondaryAnchor="Book Kanha Safari Package"
      tertiaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/faq/"
      tertiaryAnchor="Kanha Geography FAQ"
    />

    <h2>Geographic Overview</h2>

    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Location</strong></td><td>Central India, Madhya Pradesh</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Districts</strong></td><td>Mandla and Balaghat</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Total Core Area</strong></td><td>940 sq km</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Buffer Zone</strong></td><td>1,067 sq km</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Elevation Range</strong></td><td>600-900 meters</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Highest Point</strong></td><td>Sulkum Dongar (924m)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Major Range</strong></td><td>Maikal Hills (Satpura Range extension)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Coordinates</strong></td><td>22.27°N, 80.61°E</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Geological Formation</strong></td><td>Deccan plateau basalt base</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Terrain Features</h2>

    <h3>Meadows (Dadars)</h3>
    <p>
      The most distinctive feature of Kanha's geography is its meadows, locally called "dadars." These
      flat-bottomed valleys form the iconic Kanha landscape:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hallon Meadow:</strong> Largest meadow, prime tiger habitat</li>
      <li><strong>Banjar Meadow:</strong> Drained by Banjar River, mixed herds</li>
      <li><strong>Sonph Meadow:</strong> Excellent Barasingha viewing</li>
      <li><strong>Maasahi Meadow:</strong> Compact, high wildlife density</li>
      <li><strong>Sulkum Meadow:</strong> Higher elevation meadow</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Sal Forests</h3>
    <p>
      Sal (Shorea robusta) dominates Kanha's forest cover:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Approximately 70% of forested area</li>
      <li><strong>Characteristics:</strong> Tall trees (20-30m), dense canopy</li>
      <li><strong>Best Examples:</strong> Kisli Zone and dense parts of Kanha Zone</li>
      <li><strong>Wildlife:</strong> Tigers, leopards, gaur, deer</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Bamboo Thickets</h3>
    <p>
      Bamboo (Dendrocalamus strictus) forms dense understory in many areas:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Scattered throughout but concentrated in specific zones</li>
      <li><strong>Characteristics:</strong> Dense, regenerating rapidly</li>
      <li><strong>Best Examples:</strong> Mukki Zone, parts of Kanha Zone</li>
      <li><strong>Wildlife:</strong> Tigers use bamboo for cover, specialized bamboo birds</li>
      <li><strong>Management:</strong> Periodic clearing to maintain habitat diversity</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Mixed Deciduous Forests</h3>
    <p>
      Beyond pure Sal, Kanha features mixed deciduous forests:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Tree Species:</strong> Teak, tendu, mahua, bel, and others</li>
      <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Transition areas between Sal forests and meadows</li>
      <li><strong>Wildlife:</strong> Diverse bird species, smaller mammals</li>
    </ul>

