    <h2>Major Rivers and Water Sources</h2>

    <h3>Banjar River</h3>
    <p>
      The most significant river in Kanha, flowing through the park's core:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Length in Park:</strong> Approximately 35 km</li>
      <li><strong>Tributaries:</strong> Multiple perennial streams</li>
      <li><strong>Wildlife Significance:</strong> Critical water source for tigers, leopards, deer</li>
      <li><strong>Zones:</strong> Borders Kanha and Mukki zones</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Sonph River</h3>
    <p>
      Important tributary feeding Sonph Meadow:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Significance:</strong> Maintains Sonph meadow habitat</li>
      <li><strong>Wildlife:</strong> Barasingha concentrate here during dry season</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Sulkum River</h3>
    <p>
      Flows through northern Kanha Zone:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Significance:</strong> Water source for northern wildlife populations</li>
      <li><strong>Terrain:</strong> Flows through higher elevation areas</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Halon River</h3>
    <p>
      Tributary of the Banjar:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Significance:</strong> Seasonal water source</li>
      <li><strong>Wildlife:</strong> Attracts diverse bird species</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Elevation and Topography</h2>

    <p>
      Kanha's elevation profile influences habitat distribution:
    </p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Elevation Zone</th><th>Height (m)</th><th>Habitat Type</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Lowland Valleys</td><td>600-700</td><td>Meadows, riverine forests</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Mid-Elevation</td><td>700-800</td><td>Sal forests, mixed deciduous</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Plateau</td><td>800-900</td><td>Drier forests, rocky areas</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Highest Peak (Sulkum Dongar)</td><td>924</td><td>Rocky plateau habitat</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Climate Zones</h2>

    <h3>Tropical Monsoon Climate</h3>
    <p>
      Kanha experiences a tropical monsoon climate with three distinct seasons:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Summer (March-May):</strong> Hot, dry; 25-45°C</li>
      <li><strong>Monsoon (June-September):</strong> Heavy rainfall; 25-35°C</li>
      <li><strong>Winter (October-February):</strong> Cool, dry; 10-25°C</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Rainfall Pattern</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Annual Rainfall:</strong> 1,400-1,600 mm (mostly June-September)</li>
      <li><strong>Monsoon Impact:</strong> Park closed during peak monsoon</li>
      <li><strong>Dry Season:</strong> October-May, ideal for safaris</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How Geography Shapes Wildlife</h2>

    <h3>Tiger Distribution</h3>
    <p>
      Tiger territories at Kanha align with geographic features:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Tigers favor:</strong> Meadow edges, waterhole areas, bamboo thickets</li>
      <li><strong>Density highest:</strong> Where multiple habitat types converge</li>
      <li><strong>Mukki Zone advantage:</strong> Diverse terrain supports high density</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Barasingha Habitat</h3>
    <p>
      The hard-ground Barasingha depends on specific geographic features:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Requires:</strong> Open meadows with short grass</li>
      <li><strong>Concentrated in:</strong> Sonph, Maasahi, Hallon, Banjar meadows</li>
      <li><strong>Vulnerability:</strong> Meadow succession threatens habitat</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Bird Distribution</h3>
    <p>
      Different bird species prefer different geographic features:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Forest birds:</strong> Dense Sal forests (Kisli Zone)</li>
      <li><strong>Meadow birds:</strong> Open grasslands (Kanha Zone)</li>
      <li><strong>Water birds:</strong> River systems and waterholes</li>
      <li><strong>Raptors:</strong> Higher elevations and forest edges</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Buffer Zone Geography</h2>

    <p>
      The 1,067 sq km buffer zone surrounds the core area:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Purpose:</strong> Provides transition between core zone and human settlements</li>
      <li><strong>Activities:</strong> Limited tourism, forest product collection, research</li>
      <li><strong>Wildlife:</strong> Supports wildlife dispersal and breeding</li>
      <li><strong>Management:</strong> Joint Forest Management with local communities</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Geological Significance</h2>

    <p>
      Kanha sits on ancient geological formations:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Base Rock:</strong> Deccan trap basalt from ancient volcanic activity</li>
      <li><strong>Soil:</strong> Rich black cotton soil (regur) in lowlands</li>
      <li><strong>Drainage:</strong> Multiple rivers flowing south to Godavari system</li>
      <li><strong>Age:</strong> Landscape formed over millions of years</li>
    </ul>

